ed by alternating nukes and heals.<br>
<br>
I am <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><span style="text-decoration:underline">not</span><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> suggesting that chaining is or should be the only viable mage solo strategy, but that it represents a definite limit to mage power.<br>
<br>
In response to <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Goladus</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->'s observations regarding chaining, I agree overall, but differ in my conclusions.  Chaining pets allows a mage to trade time for mana.  The fights are longer, but the down time is less compared to sustain and nuke.   It is my experience that on a given mana pool, a mage can defeat a larger opponent by chaining than sustaining and nuking.<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr><!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Goladus:</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->  I'm curious, too, what you mean by chaining pets &quot;not cutting&quot; it.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->Well, in <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>SkyFire</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, my upper limit for practical chaining was 8 pets.  Can't kill it with eight <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Greater Vocaration: Earth</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, then its not practically soloable.  I never killed anything that required ten pets, but I would consider that acceptable as well.  That means, in the time it takes for the mob to kill one pet, me and <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Gobaner</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> ought to be able to deal at least 10% damage to the mob.  When I hit <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>PoP</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> and starting testing various mobs, it seemed that even yard trash lost more like 5% health or even less per pet.  20 PTK <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>(Pets To Kill)</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->?  I don't think so.<br>
<br>
I will do some more numerical-type analysis, but my gut reaction was to give up on those mobs.  There <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><span style="text-decoration:underline">are</span><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> some mobs I can chain to death, but there are hardly any camps where I can do so.<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr><!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Goladus:</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> [I am] not eager to hand out my soloing spots and strategies anymore.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->Here I must disagree with you.  I have always shared my strategies and hunting grounds openly.  Without this board, I would not have learned about chaining pets, improved reclaim energy, the logic of evocation, yoyo rooting, etc., etc.<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr><!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Goladus:</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->  When I'm not competing, I would guess an aa in 5 hours<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->That strikes me as a reasonable rate of return on time invested.  If mage soloing does not involve kiting, mages ought to be able to solo in tight areas where kiting is either impossible or inconvenient.<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr><!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Itsastony:</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->  I like it way better to kill 3 mobs per hours and get 6 blues in AA then killing shrooms like mad in FG for the same amount of exp and in the same time....The old feeling I had when soloing gargoyles in OOT is back.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->Perhaps all mages are lacking then are <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>cajones</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, the big kills.  That is in part why we debate these issues: to identify assumptions and compare them to facts.<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr><!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Itsastony:</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->  That has truly diminished when Luclin came out. Well PoP brought it back, just there are not enough mobs to choose from for us mages.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->You may well be right.<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr><!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Immlazen:</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->  Personally, I dont think Magicians should only have to chaincast to be able to solo. Im also tired of that being the crutch for those who do like to chaincast. Its like a one track mind with blinders on.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->Please read my comments at the top of this post.  Chaining is a useful criteria to estimate what is and is not practical.<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr><!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Immlazen:</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->  We were given items by Verant to give to pets to make them stronger and better. Chaincasting does not allow this. Therefore, why would we try to get all those swords, and belts, etc if we are not going to use them and keep pets alive?<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->Because mages have <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><span style="text-decoration:underline">two</span><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> major soloing tactics: chaining and sustaining pets.  Before the new pet summons, the balance was clearly in favor of chaining.  The new pet summons move the balance more in favor of sustaining.  Both remain, or ought to remain, valid choices.<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr><!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Imlazzen:</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->  I feel Magician pets need a upgrade.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->While this is a popular opinion, I think that mages will be hard pressed to argue in favor of even stronger pets.  Mages currently enjoy a relative peak of power, and proposing that mages should be made stronger is unlikely to be a priority for <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Verant</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->.  There are other classes which probably have more serious problems.<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr><!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Immlazen:</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->  why should Magicians be the only one penalized<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->The logic is hard to escape.  With mobs hitting harder than ever, tankers, who keep the enemy at bay by taking damage, must necessarily suffer.  However, kiters and charmers, who avoid or take advantage of mob melee, do not suffer or even thrive.  If mage <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>PoP</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> soloing is deficient, then I really see only three alternatives:<br>
<br>
1) Make mages better at tanking, e.g., tougher pets,<br>
2) Allow mages to kite, e.g., adding snare to post-50 fire pet spell repetoire, or<br>
3) Bypass <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>PoP</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> mobs, e.g., allowing adequate soloing outside <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>PoP</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->.<br>
<br>
The third option does not involve making mages stronger, and allows others to solo as well.<br>
<br>
However, <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Goladus</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->'s observation that <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Luclin</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> soloing was <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><span style="text-decoration:underline">too</span><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> easy should be born in mind.<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr><!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Adori:</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->  I start wondering if i play a completely different game than some of you...So get used to harder fights again.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->Alright.  What kind of fights, then?<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr><!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Immlazen:</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->  but when the ratio is 100/2 infavor of people not being able to solo what do you think the answer is. Statistically speaking that is.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->A majority can still be wrong.  Assumptions often crumple in the face of testing.<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr><!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Immlazen:</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->  I think sometimes these ones that come here and say I can...I can...I can, hurt the Mages as a whole.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->Ah, the famous <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Rthen Hypothesis</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, that positive statements about mage strength invite mage nerfs.<br>
<br>
In general, I find that objective and considered discussions of mage strengths and weaknesses pay off in the long run.  While transvergance was nerfed, mages as whole have become stronger in the last two years, primarily as a result of an open discussion of pet advantages and disadvantages.<br>
<br>
Besides, it makes little sense to argue in favor of an unneeded upgrade.  If all mages really need are better tactics, then we can solve <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><span style="text-decoration:underline">that</span><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> ourselves with this forum.<br>
<br>
I am in agreement with the <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Gospel of Improved Reclaim Energy</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> according to <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Brother Jochan</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->.  He is an example of what this forum means to me.  I have learned much from him and others sharing their tactics and analysis.  They inspire me to share what I have learned.<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr><!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Immlazen:</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->  [Goladus, W]hy are you trying so hard to prove that Mages can solo efficiently?<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->According to <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Goladus:</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>I didn't and don't make any claims about being able to solo steadily to 65. However I will also say that my whole life as a mage I did not ever solo steadily. I did a lot of soloing but it was an unsteady ride most of the way to 60.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->And I am concerned primarily about being <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><span style="text-decoration:underline">adequate</span><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> soloers.<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr><!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Immlazen:</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->  we should be able to solo dark blue the same as the other classes just like we could before POP...why do we have to settle for light blue when others are soloing dark blues easier then we can solo a light blue. We were once very good at soloing and it is the reason alot of us chose to become Mages.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->So far as I can recall, many other classes have almost always been better than mages at soloing.  Mages have always been adequate soloers.  If that has changed, I am concerned.  I am less concerned about <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>&quot;keeping up with the Joneses,&quot;</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> e.g. wizards and druids, except in so far as understanding why they can solo sheds light on my ability to solo.<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr><!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Immlazen:</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->  why try to go against the grain<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->It may be the case that the majority opinion is wrong.  I resist being stampeded.  That is in part why we argue about what <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><span style="text-decoration:underline">is</span><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END-->, and not just what is <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><span style="text-decoration:underline">believed</span><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END-->.<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr><!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Goladus:</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->  The ambiguity of the word &quot;effecient&quot; causes this confusion.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->That is why I prefer <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><span style="text-decoration:underline">adequate</span><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> instead.  What I want to avoid is the situation where casual mages, ones with only a few hours to play at a time, to be unable to advance their character at a reasonable rate.  Many mages have complained, and I have personally found soloing post-61 very frustrating so far.<br>
<br>
There may in fact be no problem here, except ignorance.  But then, sharing information is what this forum is for.<br>
<br>
